{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492476"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1073"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1073"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.15,0.33,0.04,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102730"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1073"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85213"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102730"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of increasing abdominal pain. The pain is constant and spread all over her abdomen. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. Her regular medications are metformin and perindopril. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her abdomen is diffusely tender. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute appendicitis","Perforated diverticulitis","Mesenteric ischaemia","Acute pancreatitis","Gastric outlet obstruction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows gas in the portal vein (Image 1) and areas of pneumatosis intestinalis in the mid small bowel (Image 2). Taken together with the clinical picture of diffuse abdominal pain and tachycardia, these radiological findings are highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Emesenteric ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E with probable bowel infarction. Hepatic portal venous gas can have several different origins, but mesenteric ischaemia is the most common and concerning cause. Mesenteric ischaemia occurs when there is inadequate blood flow to the intestines, leading to tissue damage and potential necrosis. It can be caused by arterial occlusion (embolism or thrombosis), venous thrombosis, or non-occlusive processes. The patient\u0027s risk factors of diabetes and hypertension increase her susceptibility to this condition. The stomach is distended likely due to decreased peristalsis of the ischaemic bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right lower quadrant pain and tenderness, rather than diffuse abdominal pain. The classic progression is periumbilical pain migrating to the right lower quadrant over 12-24 hours, often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and low-grade fever. While it can occasionally cause portal venous gas, this is rare and would not explain the small bowel pneumatosis intestinalis seen in this case. Additionally, the patient\u0027s age and the diffuse nature of her pain make appendicitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforated diverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually causes localized pain in the left lower quadrant, not diffuse abdominal pain. It typically affects older adults and is characterized by abdominal pain, fever, and changes in bowel habits. Although it can rarely lead to portal venous gas, it would not typically cause the extensive pneumatosis intestinalis seen in this patient\u0027s CT scan. Perforated diverticulitis would more likely show localized inflammation, free air, or an abscess on CT imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause diffuse abdominal pain, but the CT findings are not consistent with this diagnosis. Pancreatitis typically shows pancreatic inflammation, peripancreatic fluid collections, or fat stranding, none of which are mentioned in this case. The pain in pancreatitis is often epigastric and radiates to the back, and is frequently associated with nausea and vomiting. While pancreatitis can be severe, it would not typically cause portal venous gas or pneumatosis intestinalis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric outlet obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with vomiting, upper abdominal distension, and a succussion splash on examination. It is often caused by peptic ulcer disease, malignancy, or strictures. The CT findings of portal venous gas and pneumatosis intestinalis are not characteristic of this condition. Gastric outlet obstruction would more likely show a dilated stomach with a transition point at the pylorus or proximal duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMesenteric ischaemia is a surgical emergency associated with a high mortality rate. The presence of portal venous gas and pneumatosis intestinalis on CT, combined with the clinical picture of diffuse abdominal pain and tachycardia in a patient with risk factors (diabetes and hypertension), makes this the most likely diagnosis. Urgent surgical consultation and intervention are typically required in such cases. Treatment often involves exploratory laparotomy, resection of non-viable bowel, and measures to restore blood flow to the affected area. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for improving outcomes in this life-threatening condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gas in the portal vein must always raise the possible diagnosis of mesenteric ischaemia.","Mesenteric ischaemia can present with diffuse abdominal pain and is associated with a high mortality rate.","CT findings of portal venous gas and pneumatosis intestinalis are highly suggestive of mesenteric ischaemia."],"references":["About B, Hachem JE, Yazbeck T, et al. Hepatic portal venous gas: Physiopathology, etiology, prognosis and treatment. World J Gastroenterol 2009; 15:3585-90. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2721230/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85213"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15340"},{"type":"media","id":"15341"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20423"},{"type":"media","id":"20424"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15340"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/28d5cd06-bc7f-468d-ab97-fac76d01daf2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/28d5cd06-bc7f-468d-ab97-fac76d01daf2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":757,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"15341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15341"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/787debeb-5571-41b3-8eb7-141e46075c1a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/78